SUMMARY:Haiti's Upcoming Elections: Geopolitical Implications for the Ame
 ricas
DESCRIPTION:Haiti's forthcoming elections\, expected by the end of this y
 ear\, represent a critical turning point not only for the country's democ
 ratic trajectory but also for regional stability across the Americas. Thi
 s webinar will examine the political\, security\, and institutional conte
 xt shaping the electoral process\, including governance challenges\, publ
 ic trust\, and the capacity of Haiti's Provisional Electoral Council (CEP
 ) to maintain the current timetable that sets the first round for August 
 30 and the second round for Dec. 5.  Panelists will explore how election 
 outcomes may influence Haiti's relationships with key regional and intern
 ational actors\, affect migration patterns\, and shape approaches to secu
 rity cooperation\, economic engagement\, and humanitarian response. The d
 iscussion will also assess broader implications for democratic norms and 
 geopolitical alignments in the Caribbean and the wider Western Hemisphere
 .  Designed for policymakers\, researchers\, civil society leaders\, inte
 rnational affairs students\, and the general public\, this webinar offers
  timely insights into why Haiti's elections matter far beyond its borders
 \, and what is at stake for the future of regional cooperation in the Ame
 ricas.Panelists:Robert Fatton\, Jr.\, Julia A. Cooper Professor of Govern
 ment and Foreign Affairs in the Department of Politics at the University 
 of Virginia\, and a leading scholar of Haitian politics and democracy  Wo
 lf Pamphile\, founder and executive director of Haiti Policy House (https
 ://www.haitipolicyhouse.org/)Greg Beckett\, Associate Professor of Anthro
 pology at Western University and author of There Is No More Haiti: Betwee
 n Life and Death in Port-au-PrinceModerator:Websder Corneille\, Adjunct L
 ecturer at Indiana University Bloomington    &#160\;  Hosted by the Cente
 r for Latin American and Caribbean Studies (CLACS) at Indiana University 
 Bloomington\, this roundtable is co-supported by Haiti Policy House (http
 s://www.haitipolicyhouse.org/)\, a Washington\, D.C.â€“based think tank f
 ocused on geopolitical issues specific to Haiti\, and the Canada-Caribbea
 n Institute (CCI) (https://canadacaribbeaninstitute.org/institute-gov/)\,
  a collaborative network founded in 2020 by The University of the West In
 dies and Brock University to improve quality of life in Canada and the Ca
 ribbean.  &#160\;  For more information\, feel free to contact clacs@iu.e
 du or wecorne@iu.edu.  &#160\; Meeting URL: https://iu.zoom.us/j/85062058
 835
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Haiti's forthcoming elections\, expecte
 d by the end of this year\, represent a critical turning point not only f
 or the country's democratic trajectory but also for regional stability ac
 ross the Americas. This webinar will examine the political\, security\, a
 nd institutional context shaping the electoral process\, including govern
 ance challenges\, public trust\, and the capacity of Haiti's <em>Provisio
 nal Electoral Council</em> (CEP) to maintain the current timetable that s
 ets the first round for August 30 and the second round for Dec. 5.</p><p>
   Panelists will explore how election outcomes may influence Haiti's rela
 tionships with key regional and international actors\, affect migration p
 atterns\, and shape approaches to security cooperation\, economic engagem
 ent\, and humanitarian response. The discussion will also assess broader 
 implications for democratic norms and geopolitical alignments in the Cari
 bbean and the wider Western Hemisphere.</p><p>  Designed for policymakers
 \, researchers\, civil society leaders\, international affairs students\,
  and the general public\, this webinar offers timely insights into why Ha
 iti's elections matter far beyond its borders\, and what is at stake for 
 the future of regional cooperation in the Americas.</p><p><strong>Panelis
 ts:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Robert Fatton\, Jr</strong>.\, Julia A. C
 ooper Professor of Government and Foreign Affairs in the Department of Po
 litics at the University of Virginia\, and a leading scholar of Haitian p
 olitics and democracy  </li><li><strong>Wolf Pamphile</strong>\, founder 
 and executive director of <em><a href="https://www.haitipolicyhouse.org/"
 >Haiti Policy House</a></em></li><li><strong>Greg Beckett</strong>\, Asso
 ciate Professor of Anthropology at Western University and author of <em>T
 here Is No More Haiti: Between Life and Death in Port-au-Prince</em></li>
 </ul><p><strong>Moderator</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Websder Corneille<
 /strong>\, Adjunct Lecturer at Indiana University Bloomington  </li></ul>
 <p>  &#160\;</p><p>  Hosted by the <strong>Center for Latin American and 
 Caribbean Studies</strong> (CLACS) at Indiana University Bloomington\, th
 is roundtable is co-supported by <strong><a href="https://www.haitipolicy
 house.org/">Haiti Policy House</a></strong>\, a Washington\, D.C.â€“based
  think tank focused on geopolitical issues specific to Haiti\, and the <s
 trong><a href="https://canadacaribbeaninstitute.org/institute-gov/">Canad
 a-Caribbean Institute (CCI)</a>\,</strong> a collaborative network founde
 d in 2020 by The University of the West Indies and Brock University to im
 prove quality of life in Canada and the Caribbean.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>
